<p rend="left">so that the furrows are a little deeper at the bottom than at the top</p>
<p>I cut two trenches 18 in deep from ridge to ridge one just before the slope died out marked D in sketch above &amp; one after—at the furrow marked E a little below— the depth of furrow was 6<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></formula> inches. There is a difference in the texture &amp; color of the soil between top &amp; bottom of each trench but it is so gradual &amp; so slight you can not put your finger any where on a division between the two</p>
<p>Scarcely any wormcasts to be seen— we never are much plagued with them in the garden</p> 
